C. Dart, adver\ntiiinc manager. Lawrence C Daily\nai Arthur J. Wse. of the New York\ntSee, assisted in the arrangements\nA i.ucueou of the Franklin contin?\nent was held at the Commodore at 1\n?\"clock. S. E. Ackerman, sales man\nlier, presided, and C. C. Parlin, of the\nC-rtis Publishing Company, addressed\n:he 200 diners on the business outlook\nfor 1021. Mr. Parlin said there was no\nMStion about the prospects for the\n.ear, \"if every one in the trade got\nbusy.' Another luncheon ??as that\ngiven by the Stevens-Duryea officials\nlocal and visiting newspaper men.\nIndustry Depicted on Screen\nAn educational feature of show week\n?vas the showing of \"The Porcelain\nLamp,\" at the Strand, a five-reel filra\n?vhich depicts in interesting fashion\ntie history of vehicular transportation\nfrom primitive days to the present\nThe S!m Shows with remarkable clar?\nity and simplicity the operation of a\ngasoline motor. The picture ge*s its\nname from an explosion of a porcelain\nlamp which ?gave a Trench inventor the\nkey to automotive transportation.\nPreceding the showing short ad?\ndresses were made by Grover C.\nWhaien, of the Department of Plant\n?ad Structures, and Thomas Moore, ex?\necutive secretary of the New York\nAutomobile Dealers' Association. Prom?\ninent local educators, high school\npupils, automotive experts and hun?\ndreds of **risiting dealers witnessed the\npieturization, which was under the\nauspices of the National Automobile\nChamber of Commerce.\nThat the body types which will pre?\nvail the coming year will be confined\nto the five-passenger tomring car, two\npsssenger runabout, five-passenger\nledan and four-passenger coupe, with\nseven-passenger touring cars and\n?even-passenger sedan3 in limited num?\nbers, was predicted by George J.\nMercer, consulting body engineer of\ntoe Saxon Motor Company, at a se?sion\no: the Society of Automotive Engi?\nneers. The reduction in number of\near types was ascribed to the apparent\n?-?nal demand for the smaller m??\ncame?.\nLighter Car Era Predicted\nColonel Jesse G. Vincent, outgoing\npr?sidant of the 8. A. E, told the mem\n2? M *Dot*Ier session yesterday that\nm problems at present confronting\nwe sutomotive industry were embraced\nThe ?daily crowds at\nthe National ?Sextet\n?exhibit indicate that\nthe pubjic knows and\nappreciates a truly\nfiae inn-tor carriage.\nFaertaer Motor Car Co.\n1759 Broadway\nSfw York\nMM B-.tfor.-l At?.\nBrooklyn\nAUBURN\n\"Wy-SIX\n2? Auburn Beauty*\n?X enters its twenty'\nyear pre^etoinent\n?to the twenty'first\nJ*o?obile show. So will\nrj?er itt one hundred\n^enty-f?st year.\nHot ^aaW^^^\nLaFav^tto Four-Door Coupe\nEvery stc- ..e uns car its independently accessible. It is an eight-cylinder\ncar of advance design, manufactured by the LaFayette Motors Com?\npany, of Mars Hills, Indianapolis.\nin roads, fuels and costs. Misunder?\nstanding on the part of the pub.ic as\nto the actual expense of operating a\nmotor car or truck had been responsi?\nble, to a great degree, for detrimental\nconditions prevailing. He assailed\nlegislators who seek to impose addi?\ntional taxes on cars and predicted an\nera of lighter cars with higher gaso?\nline mileage.\nThe Motor and Accessory Manufac?\nturers' Association also held its annual\nsessions yesterday. After a \"speech?\nless banquet\" at the Commodore, the\nseveral hundred members were treated\n?to-a show not altogether in\" their line.\nIt was provide<l by the cast of the\n\"Midnight Frolic. Sidney S. Meyers,\ngeneral counsel of the association,\nsupervised the program. Charles E.\nThompson, president, opened the fes?\ntivities.\nPublic Emulates S. A. E.\nIn Mechanical Queries\nThe technical man in charge of th-?\nLafayette chassis, on the third floor\nof the Grand Central Palace, has been\namazed this week by the knowledge of\nmotor car mechanics displayed by the\npublic.\n\"What is the weight of this chassis?\"\n\"How high is the center of gravity?\"\n\"How many bearings has the crank?\nshaft?\"\"* These are common questions\nfrom women, as well as from the suo\nposedly better informed sex.\nThe Lafayette chassis, which is fin?\nished in natural metals, resplendent in\ncopper, polished steel and nickel. w.-:s\nr-nilt under the direction of D. McCall\nWhite, whose foreign chassis have *it\ntracteii wide attention in the Olympia\n;h.-'-.vs of London in past years.\nThe Lafayette, according to Mr.\nWhite, represents the first successful\nblending of American and European\nmanufacturing methods. After design?\ning and building some of the lead.ncr\ncars of Europe, he became associate!\nwith one of the leading builders of fine\ncars in this eountry.\nI Pierce-Arrow Is\nProud of Its\nNewest Models\nI\nPerformance of Earlier\nDual-Valve Engine Is Sur?\npassed by New Type;\nModernity of Body Lines\nA new Pierce-Arrow line makes its\nformal bow at the Automobile Show.\nI Advanced show'ngs of the new models\nin New York caused them to be com\npared impartially with the best that\nforeign makers have to offer, and\nj critics have said that in appearance.\nadvance in mechanical design and\nstandards of workmanship these carp\ncan hold their own with anything yet\ncreated in the automobile world.\nProduction will be continued of the\n38-horsepower and 48-horsepower\nright-hand drive models, which offer\nthe option of a ranee of body styles\nnot included in the added type of car.\nLikewise this policy gives the user a\nchoice between the right-hand and ?eft\nhand control, the latter being a feature\nof the newly announced model.\nThe departure reflected in the design\nof tach of the ten types of bodies of\nthe new model does not rob the car;.\nof established characteristics, yet a\nmarked modernity of appearance i-i\n?Tected.\nWhether measured by rapidity of\nacceleration, speed, flexibility, freedom\nfrom vibration, economy oi operation\nor power, the performance of the now\nPierce-Arrow is a revelation, it is de?\nclared.\n\"The performance of the. dual valve\ntype of engine introduced two years\n?..??;o by the Pierce-Arrow Motor Car\nCompany until now has never been\nequalled,\" says C. W. Cady, passenger\near sales manager of the Harro'd.-.\nMotor Car Company. \"The oual valve\nValue Per Dollar\nInvested\nThere is a vivid suggestion of man?\nliness, character and physical prowess in\nthe graceful lines and appearance of the\n?sturdy Stutz.\nEvery Stutz car is built to withstand\nevery conceivable strain or shock. By\nexacting comparison-feature by feature\n-with any other car, Stutz gives you the\ngreatest value per dollar invested. Proof\nis here ready for you.\nWe will be pleased to show you the\ncomplete line of Stutz cars.\nWm. Parkinson Motor Sales Co.\n1796 Broadway, Now York City\nBrooklyn Newark\nU68 Bedford Ave. 372 Centrai Ane.\nST?TZ MOTOR CAR CO. OF AMERICA, Inc.\nI AUTO SHOW SPACE B-26\nHoCo&a MOT?SE <CAU> COMIRAr*fV\nINDIANAPOLIS U. ?9.A.\nmtumr Gasnvra, reates**\ni engine which powers the new Pierce\nArrow yields results which, point for\npoint, enhance the standards set by its\npredecessor.\"\n\"In one sense the Pierce-Arrow is\ncssentiaily a woman's car,\" says Mr.\nCady. \"To drive a Pierce-Arrow is a\npleasure, not a task. The slightest of\neffort is required to steer. Gear shift?\ning can be done easily, even by a nov?\nice, because of an overrunning inter?\nmediate gear?an exclusive feature. A\nj light pressure depresses the clutch and\nlirake pedals. A new type of foot ac\nj celeratpr permita the foot to rest upon\nitdtaturaliy for hours without fatigue\n\"A noticeable improvement ha? beer\neffected in the riding qualities. A\nI scientifically designed spring su_pen\ni ?rfon permit-?, of a high speed ovei\ni rough roads without jounce or side\nsways.\"\nThe open models include a two-pas\n1 nenger runabout and four, six ant\nseven-passenger cars. The close*\ni modela are the limousine, coup? sedan\nj sedan, vestibule sedan, brougham anc\ni iandaulet.\n-1\nFifty-three Car Makes\nUse AC Spark Plug\nFifty-three makes of cars on displa\n1 this week at the National Automoriii\nShow are equipped with AC spar'\nplugs, a3 against thirty-one makes o\ncars equipped with other plug?-? all o\nwhich, in the words of the exhibitor\nof thi?i plug, justifies the essertion tha\nAC plugs \"dominate the show,\"\nThe AC plug is manufactured by th\nChampion Ignition Company, of Flin\nMich., and a list of the cars using\nfollows:\nAmerican Beauty, Anderson, Appei\nson, Auburn, Buick, Cadillac, Cas?\nChandler, Chevrolet, Cleveland, Col?\nCommonwealth, Davis, Dodg?. Dort, d\nPont, Hatneld, Hanson, Haynes, Hy?\nson, Hupmobile, Jackson, Kissel Ka\nLe.fayette, Liberty, Locomobile. Loi\niaine, Maibohm, Marmon, McF?r.l?i\nMitchell, ?Monroe, Nash. Noma. Ni\ntional, Oakland, Oldsmobile, Packap\nPaige, Paterson, Pierce-Arrow, Pilo\nPremier, Reo, Roamer, R. V.' Knigh\nSaxon, Scripps-Booth, Standard, Stearn,\nStevens-Durvea and Westcott.\nI How Can an Auto\nEnjoy Similar\nRepute All Over?\n.1..\nAnswer Is, According to Dan\nj iels, It Cair t Be Done, but\nCourtesy Can Be Shown Jjy\nAll Dealers in Country\nBy H. S. Daniels\nj Advertising Manager, Dort Motor\nCar Company\nSome people wonder how it is possi?\nble for a motor car to enjoy a like\nreputation in various parts of the conn\ntry when it is in the hands of so many\ndifferent types and grades of dealers.\nThe answer is that it isn't possible.\nBut much may be done, nevertheless,\nto standardize many elements that\nmake for a happy relationship between\nthe dealer and the buyer.\nThe company building the car, as well\nas the car itself, is judged largely bj\nj the policy of its local representation\nThe courtesy, fairness and disposition\nto serve on the part of the dealer eithe;\nkeeps a car sold or, so to speak, \"un\nsells\" it.\nIn fact, no matter how good a piece o:\nmechanism a car may be, it can easil*\ncome into disrepute through the atti\ntude toward the public of the deale\nwho handles it. In other words, satis\nj faction with a motor car .argely de\npends upon who is on the ground t\nspeak for, it and its maker.\nRealizing the importance of a uni\nform p'olicy in the treatment of owner\nand prospective owners, we started tw\nyears ago what is called the \"Dot.\npepfcllows.\" A \"pepfellow\" is a Dor\ndealer who can qualify on twenty-si\nTha Eight vaith Eight? Loss Parta\nNo\nother\nEight\n?is so\ndesigned!\nTwo simple \"fours\"?merged into\none?is the design that gives\nApperson?the remarkable com?\nbination of?four cylinder\neconomy plus eight cylinder\nflexibility. Drive an Apperson\nfirst?then decide.\nSee the smart Apperton\nModela at the Show!\n?FTERSON BROS. AUTOMOBILE COMPANY\nKokomo, Indiana\nC T. SILVE1\nMO W?MC f 7th Strcat\ngfoXSSSSSSKSSXSS^XS^^\nBe sure to ride in it\n?before you buy any\nother car.\nbl\nIX\nAuto Show\nSpace B-12\nor\ni^g^^^^^\n1692\nBroadway\nI questions concerning his method and\nmanner of- conducting business. It is\ni not eniirel*, easy for a dealer to become\na 100 per cent pepfellow, but we haye.\ni nevertheless, awarded the emblem that i\nI symbolizes it to a goodly percentage i\nof our organization, and the \"full fledg- j\ners\" are constantly increasing.\nThis means much in good will to the i\ncar and the manufacturer, and by the\nI same token it means even more to the\n1 purchaser of a Dort ear. By following\nj the rues which the \"pepfellow\" plan\n1 automatically creates, the dealer equips\nJ himself for courteous, convenient and\nj thorough service, thereby insuring the\nj owner prompt and intelligent counsel\nI and aid whenever they are-i required.\nThere are now several hundred Dort\ndealers who have passed the \"pepfel\nj low\" examination, more than So per\ncent, and the number is constantly in-\ni creasing.\nStandardization Makes\nSales, Says Mulholland\nThe relation of truck bodies to truck\nsales is brought out largely through j\nstandardization of the bodies, accord- i\ning to O. B. Mulholland, of Mulholland\nStandardized Bodies, who was in New\